The problem is that your `Counter` class does automatic unboxing of the stored value. You need to declare it as:

    class Counter {
        private final AtomicStampedReference&lt;Integer&gt; value;
    
        public Counter(int initialValue) {
            value = new AtomicStampedReference&lt;&gt;(initialValue, 1000);
        }
    
        public int getValue() {
            return value.getReference();
        }
    
        public int increment() {
            int[] stampHolder = new int[1];
            Integer current;
            int next;
            do {
                current = value.get(stampHolder);
                next = current + 1;
            } while (!value.compareAndSet(current, next, stampHolder[0], stampHolder[0] + 1));
    
            return next;
        }
    }

When declaring `Integer current` in the `increment()` method the `current` variable can hold a reference to the `Integer` object stored in the `AtomicStampedReference&lt;Integer&gt;` and therefore the `expectedReference == current.reference` condition can be true.

---
As you have noticed, with

            int[] stampHolder = new int[1];
            int current;
            int next;
            do {
                current = value.get(stampHolder);
                next = current + 1;
            } while (!value.compareAndSet(current, next, stampHolder[0], stampHolder[0] + 1));

the line `current = value.get(stampHolder);` will unbox the `Integer` value in the `AtomicStampedReference&lt;&gt;` and for int values &gt;= 128 the boxing of `current` in the call `value.compareAndSet(current, next, stampHolder[0], stampHolder[0] + 1))` will create a new `Integer`.

However, with

            int[] stampHolder = new int[1];
            Integer current;
            int next;
            do {
                current = value.get(stampHolder);
                next = current + 1;
            } while (!value.compareAndSet(current, next, stampHolder[0], stampHolder[0] + 1));

the line `current = value.get(stampHolder)` will just read the reference to the `Integer` value stored in the `AtomicStampedReference&lt;&gt;` and `value.compareAndSet(current, next, stampHolder[0], stampHolder[0] + 1))` will pass **that same** reference as first argument in the call and therefore the condition `expectedReference == current.reference` is true (assuming that no other thread changed the value)

